          <h1>Non-Destructive Testing</h1>
          <br>
          <br>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Nondestructive
              Testing is an examination, evaluation or inspection of an object
              in a manner that will not impair the future usefulness of the
              object. <br>
            </font></p>
          <p> <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><em>OR</em></font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Nondestructive
            </font><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">testing
              is: the development and application of technical methods to
              examine materials or components in ways that do not impair
              futureusefulness and serviceability in order to detect, locate,
              measure and evaluate discontinuities, defects and other
              imperfections; to assess integrity, properties and composition;
              and to measure geometrical characteristics. (ASTM E1316-92, <em>Standard
                Terminology for Nondestructive Examinations</em>). </font> </p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Nondestructive
              testing (NDT) may be referred to as NDI (Inspection), and/or NDE
              (Examination or Evaluation). </font></p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">In
              general, the field of NDT employs radiographic, ultrasonic,
              magnetic, particle, liquid penetrant, visual, thermal, acoustic,
              differential pressure, etc., techniques.&nbsp;</font></p>
          <p align="justify"><br>
            <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong><font color="#000099"><em>What
                    is NDT used for?</em></font></strong></font><br>
            <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong>To
                detect flaws (internal or external);</strong></font></p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong>To
                measure thickness, density, etc.; <br>
              </strong></font></p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong>To
                &nbsp;determine structure or composition; or</strong></font></p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong>To
                measure or detect any of the object's properties.</strong></font></p>
          <p><br>
            <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><strong><font color="#990033"><em>What
                    detection methods are used for NDT?</em></font></strong></font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Any physical
              phenomena can be employed for NDT, as long as it does the
              job.&nbsp; For example: simple sight or sound. NDT can involve
              some form of electromagnetic energy or sonic or acoustic waves
              (vibrational energy). </font></p>
          <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Passive methods
            include visual inspection or acoustic emission.&nbsp; Active methods
            include Some form of energy is made incident on the object and is
            monitored as it is re-emitted from the object.&nbsp; The re-emitted
            signal can be transmitted, reflected, refracted, scattered, or there
            can be secondary emission (activation) </font>
          <p> </p>
